# Feature inventory (opys)

This project tracks what it does as a file-based inventory: one markdown file
per feature under `docs/features/`, managed by the [`opys`](https://github.com/BohdanTkachenko/opys)
CLI and verified in CI. `docs/features/INDEX.md` and `docs/views/` are
generated — read them, never edit them.

## Reading

Start from `docs/features/INDEX.md` (the small whole-inventory map), then `rg`
by tag/status, then open only the 2–5 relevant feature files. Do not bulk-read
`docs/features/`.

## Writing — always via the CLI, never hand-edit frontmatter or status

- New feature: `opys new --title "..." --tags a,b`
- Change status: `opys set-status <ID> implemented` (rejected unless a
  test-plan item is checked; `wontfix` requires `--reason`)
- Tags: `opys tag <ID> --add x --remove y`

These commands regenerate `INDEX.md`/`views/` automatically. Spec prose and
test-plan edits are normal file edits; run `opys verify` afterward — it is the
CI gate.

## Implementing a feature

1. Read the feature file fully.
2. Implement and add tests.
3. Check the covered test-plan items and append backticked test references
   (`module::test_name`); a single case may be covered by several tests.
4. `opys set-status <ID> implemented`, then `opys verify`.

Never record test results, dates, or completion claims in feature files — CI
owns automated results and committed runbooks own manual ones.
